# Acid-base Equilibria

### Acid base reaction

Conjugate acid-base pair : 
- #Definition <mark style="background: #ADCCFFA6;">Pair of reactants and products</mark> that are linked to each other
-  #Concept Differ by one proton / $H^+$

 $CH_{3}COOH (aq) + H_{2}O (l) \rightleftharpoons CH_{3}COO^{-} (aq) + H_{3}O^{+} (aq)$ 
- $CH_{3}COOH$ and $CH_{3}COO^-$ are conjugate acid-base pair
- $H_{2}O$ and $H_{3}O^+$ are conjugate acid-base pair
- There are 2 acid in this equation, which are $CH_{3}COOH$ and $H_{3}O^+$ 
- There are 2 base in this equation, which are $CH_{3}COO^-$ and $H_{2}O$

 $HCl(aq) + H_{2}O (l) \rightarrow Cl^{-} (aq) + H_{3}O^{+} (aq)$ 
 -  $HCl$ and $Cl-$ are conjugate acid-base pair
- $H_{2}O$ and $H_{3}O^+$ are conjugate acid-base pair
- There are **ONLY** 1 acid in this equation, which are $HCl$ (due to irreversible reaction)
- There are **ONLY** 1 base in this equation, which are $H_{2}O$ (due to irreversible reaction)

