### Ionic Product of Water

$H_{2}O \rightleftharpoons H^{+} + OH^-$ 
Equilibrium constant of this reaction, $K_{w} = [H^{+}][OH^-]$ 
$K_w$ is also known as ionic product of water, $K_{w} = 1.00 \times 10^{-14}$ at 279 K
#Calculation

$$
\begin{gather}
\because [H^{+}] = [OH^{-}] \\
\therefore  K_{w} = [H^{+}]^2 \\
[H^{+}] = \sqrt{1.00 \times 10^{-14}} = 1.00 \times 10^{-7}
\end{gather}
$$

---
### Strong acid-base reaction

pH: 
- #Definition Negative logarithm to base 10 of $H^{+}$ / $pH = - log_{10}{[H^{+}]}$ 
- For strong acid, since the dissociation of proton in water is complete, hence $[HA] = [H^{+}]$  for $HA \rightarrow H^{+} + OH^{-}$ 
- #Calculation If the substance is neutral ($[H^{+}] = [OH^{-}]$), $pH = - log_{10}{[1.00 \times 10^{-7}]} = 7$ 

