### Weak acid-base reaction

#Calculation
Given chemical reaction $HA (aq) \rightleftharpoons H^{+} + A^{-}$
Acid dissociation constant, $K_{a}= \frac{[H^{+}][A^{-}]}{[HA]}$

$$
\begin{gather}
\because [H^{+}] = [A^{-}] \ ,([H^{+}] \neq [HA]) \\
\therefore K_{a} = \frac{[H^{+}]^{2}}{[HA]} \\
\text{Define } pK_{a} = - log_{10}{K_a}
\end{gather}
$$

Assumption made for weak acid:
1. $[H^+]$ in water is negligible
2. $[HA]$ in equilibrium = initial $[HA]$

```ad-note
title: Concept
Note that higher the $K_a$, weaker the acid

```

