# Solubility Equilibria

Solubility:
- #Definition Number of grams or moles needed to saturate 100 g or 1 kg of water
- Equilibrium form when ionic compound is in contact with a saturated solution of its ion
- Only can used for slightly soluble salts
- Smaller $K_{sp}$ means lower solubility
- #Calculation $K_{sp} = (x \times [A^{+}])^{x}(y \times [B^{-}])^{y} \text{ for } A_{x}B_{y} \; \rightleftharpoons \; xA^{+} + yB^{-}$ , where $K_{sp}$ is solubility product at 293K

```ad-note
title: Soluble vs Dissociate

$Mg(OH)_{2} \ (s) \ \rightleftharpoons \ Mg(OH)_{2} \ (aq) \ \rightarrow \ Mg^{2+}  (aq) + 2OH^{-}  (aq)$

Notice that MgOH(s) form equilibrium with MgOH(aq), and the equilibrium coefficient in this context is solubility product, this is called partially soluble.

However, MgOH(aq) is fully ionised into its ions. Hence, the equation also can be written to $Mg(OH)_{2} \ (s) \ \rightleftharpoons \ Mg^{2+}  (aq) + 2OH^{-}  (aq)$
```


Common ion effect:
- #Concept Adding a solution with a common ion with the dissolved salt, the solubility will reduce and precipitate is formed
- By Le Chatelier's Principle, increasing concentration of ions will shift the equilibrium to left, and hence more solid form.
- #Calculation $$
\begin{gather}
\text{Define } Q_{sp} = (x \times [A^{+}])^{x}(y \times [B^{-}])^{y} \ \text{ for } A_{x}B_{y} \; \rightleftharpoons \; xA^{+} + yB^{-} \\
\text{If } Q_{sp} \textgreater K_{sp}, \text{ then it is insoluble in water. Otherwise it is soluble}
\end{gather}
$$
- Example: 
$$
AgCl(s) \rightleftharpoons Ag^{+} + Cl^{-}
$$
	- NaCl solution is added
	- $Cl^{-}$ ion is the common ion
	- The equilibrium shift to the left
	- Precipitate formed

