# Partition Coefficient

Partition coefficient:
 - #Definition Ratio of the concentration of a solute in two solvent at equilibrium
 - #Calculation Denoted by $K_{pc}$, where it can be calculated with $K_{pc} = \frac{\displaystyle [\text{A}(\text{solvent 2})\ ]}{\displaystyle [\text{A}(\text{solvent 1})\ ]}$ for $\text{A (solvent 2)} \rightleftharpoons \text{A (solvent 1)}$ 
 - #Concept Solubilities of solute varies by strength of attraction between solute and solvent
	 1. NH3 
		 - NH3 form hydrogen bond with water -> NH3 is more soluble in water
		 - NH3 form weaker id-id and pd-pd in organic solvent -> NH3 is less soluble in water
		 - Hence, $K_{sp} = \frac{\displaystyle [NH_{3} (\text{organic solvent})]}{\displaystyle [NH_{3} (\text{water})]} < 1$ .
	2. I2
		- I2 only can form id-id with both water and organic solvent -> I2 is more soluble in organic solvent
		- Hence, $K_{sp} = \frac{\displaystyle [I_{2} (\text{organic solvent})]}{\displaystyle [I_{2} (\text{water})]} > 1$ .
